Hi,

as "A Miner Problem" shows, even a distributed, p2p solution like BitCo=
in=20
suffers from a secondary centralisation flaw. Simply put, economy of sc=
ale=20
lets the biggest player or a cartel of thoise basically undermine the=20=

"decentralized" part and take control over the network.

A similar thing has happened with e-mail and GMail. GMail basically dic=
tates=20
the rules in the e-mail world, simply because they're the largest and h=
ave the=20
most users. Again, economy of scale is to blame.

So let me pose a question here: is it possible to design a protocol tha=
t does=20
not succumb to economy of scale-based secondary centralisation? Is it p=
ossible=20
to design a protocol that does not lend itself to economy of scale?

=2D-=20
Pozdrawiam,
